                            <comment id="95437" author="rwinch" created="Tue, 12 Nov 2013 07:07:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It isn&apos;t clear to me what you believe the issue to be. The patch you have proposed would break functionality because the exception notFound needs to be thrown. In short, please clarify what you believe to be broken and why.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="95543" author="oh2mqk" created="Fri, 15 Nov 2013 06:04:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The issue is that an intruder can currently use fixed password value to find out if username X exists or not.&lt;br/&gt;
This permits username existence probing with automated scripts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The solution is to run passwordEncoder.isPasswordValid() tester method with input pair that always produces &quot;BadCredentials&quot; exception result.&lt;br/&gt;
Therefore throwing &quot;notFound&quot; will not be necessary.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="95546" author="rwinch" created="Fri, 15 Nov 2013 07:05:30 +0000"  >&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I&apos;m not sure why you believe that someone can find out if the username X exists or not. Perhaps you can elaborate why you believe this to be true. As I see it
	&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The UsernameNotFoundException is caught by the AbstractUserDetailsAuthenticationProvider and turned into a BadCredentialsException. So regardless of if the user exists or a password is invalid, a BadCredentialsException is thrown.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Even if a BadCredentialsException is thrown you really shouldn&apos;t display the details of the exception or message to a user anyways. Instead if there is a failed login, give a generic error message.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The only information that &lt;b&gt;might&lt;/b&gt; be revealed is the password length. This is because the password comparison is done using a constant time comparison. So no matter what password the attacker enters it will always take the amount of time to compare every character.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The proposed solution will not work since PasswordEncoder.isPasswordValid does not throw any exceptions as defined on the interface Javadoc. It only returns true or false. So no Exception will be thrown. This change will not work. This cannot be changed since it is part of the API contract that others are coding against.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
</comment>
